ğŸ§  Tenzing and Books â€” Final Notes + Code
ğŸ’­ Problem Summary
link: https://codeforces.com/problemset/problem/1842/B
You have 3 stacks, each with n books.
Each book has a difficulty rating (non-negative integer).
Tenzingâ€™s knowledge starts at 0.
When he reads a book of difficulty v:

knowledge = knowledge | v


He can:

Choose any stack any time

Must read from top to bottom in a stack

Stop whenever he wants

Goal:
Check if he can make knowledge == x.

âš™ï¸ Key Concept (Bitwise)

To reach exactly x,
you can only use books that donâ€™t add extra bits outside x.

Condition:

(book | x) == x


If this fails, that book (and all below it in that stack) canâ€™t be read.

ğŸ” Logic (Step-by-Step)

Start with knowledge = 0

For each of the 3 stacks:

Read from top until (book | x) != x

Keep OR-ing valid books into knowledge

After all stacks:

If knowledge == x â†’ print "Yes"

Else â†’ print "No"

ğŸ’» Clean Code (C++)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t;
    cin >> t;

    while (t--) {
        int n, x;
        cin >> n >> x;

        vector<int> a(n), b(n), c(n);
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> a[i];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> b[i];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> c[i];

        int knowledge = 0;

        // Read stack A
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if ( (a[i] | x) == x )
                knowledge |= a[i];
            else break;
        }

        // Read stack B
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if ( (b[i] | x) == x )
                knowledge |= b[i];
            else break;
        }

        // Read stack C
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if ( (c[i] | x) == x )
                knowledge |= c[i];
            else break;
        }

        cout << (knowledge == x ? "Yes\n" : "No\n");
    }
}

ğŸ§® Complexity

Each stack processed once â†’ O(n) per test

Total O(sum(n)) â‰¤ 10^5 â†’ âœ… Fast

